HON_0001|Tc-99m|emission|Which emission is correct?|140 keV gamma|511 keV annihilation photons|Tc-99m emits a 140 keV gamma photon after isomeric transition. 511 keV photons are associated with positron annihilation.|1
HON_0002|Tc-99m|half_life|Which half-life is correct?|~6 hours|~8 days|Tc-99m has a physical half-life of approximately 6 hours.|1
HON_0003|Tc-99m|decay_mode|Which decay mode is correct?|Isomeric transition|Beta-minus decay|Tc-99m decays by isomeric transition to Tc-99 with emission of a 140 keV gamma photon.|1
HON_0004|Tc-99m|generation|Which production method is correct?|Mo-99/Tc-99m generator|Ge-68/Ga-68 generator|Tc-99m is commonly obtained from a Mo-99/Tc-99m generator.|1
HON_0005|F-18|emission|Which emission is correct?|Positron emission|140 keV gamma|F-18 is a positron emitter. Positron annihilation produces paired 511 keV photons detected in PET.|1
HON_0006|F-18|half_life|Which half-life is correct?|~110 minutes|~6 hours|F-18 has a physical half-life of approximately 110 minutes.|1
HON_0007|F-18|decay_mode|Which decay mode is correct?|Positron emission|Isomeric transition|F-18 decays by positron emission making it useful for PET imaging.
HON_0008|F-18|generation|Which production method is correct?|Cyclotron|Mo-99/Tc-99m generator|F-18 is cyclotron-produced rather than eluted from a Mo-99/Tc-99m generator.|1
HON_0009|Ga-68|emission|Which emission is correct?|Positron emission|Beta-minus emission|Ga-68 is a positron emitter used for PET imaging.|1
HON_0010|Ga-68|half_life|Which half-life is correct?|~68 minutes|~8 days|Ga-68 has a physical half-life of approximately 68 minutes.|1|
HON_0011|Ga-68|decay_mode|Which decay mode is correct?|Positron emission|Isomeric transition|Ga-68 decays by positron emission and is used for PET radiopharmaceuticals such as DOTATATE.|1
HON_0012|Ga-68|generation|Which production method is correct?|Ge-68/Ga-68 generator|Mo-99/Tc-99m generator|Ga-68 can be obtained from a Ge-68/Ga-68 generator.|1
HON_0013|I-123|emission|Which emission is correct?|159 keV gamma|511 keV annihilation photons|I-123 emits a principal gamma photon around 159 keV useful for gamma camera imaging.|2
